Flatline

Target IP: 10.10.26.120
Challenge Description: What are the flags?

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.26.120 -Pn -p- returns the result shown above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine. I will need to perform further aggressive scans to identify its services and application.


Performing an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.26.10 -Pn -p 3389,8021 returns the result shown above. The target machine seems to be running RDP on port 3389. And there is another unusual application on port 8021 called FreeSWITCH. The target machine is running Windows as the operating system. Since I do not have any credentials for the RDP application, I will firstly enumerate the application on port 8021.

Enumeration

Port 8021: FreeSWITCH

Connecting to the port 8021 using the command nc 10.10.26.10 8021, I did not receive anything useful as shown above. However, I notice the response from the target machine is some type of authentication via a request. After doing some Google search, I identified the password for this application is Cluecon. However, is this application vulnerable?


Doing a Google search for FreeSWITCH vulnerability, I came across the exploit shown above at Exploit DB. I downloaded the exploit shown above on my machine with the name exp.py. Time to test it now.


And bingo. The target machine seems to be vulnerable to this exploit. I ran the command python3 exp.py 10.10.26.10 whoami to execute the exploit and the target machine successfully executed the command whoami. The target machine's hostname is win-eom4pk0578n\nekrotic, as shown above.


I used the same exploit from the previous section to execute the command systeminfo on the target machine. Then I obtained the result shown above. Now I have more information about the target machine, such as the OS, OS architecture, version, applied hotfixes, etc.


Executing the command dir on the target machine returns the result shown above. The target machine seems to be currently at C:/Program Files/FreeSWITCH. Since command execution is possible. Maybe I can execute a command to create a new user, and use that account to RDP into the target machine? Even better if I can add this new user inside the local administrators group. Time to put it to test now.

Exploitation & Privilege Escalation


I had to reset the box due to instable connection. After resetting the box, it obtained the new IP address of 10.10.105.255. The payload to add a new user is the following
net user root Password123! /add && timeout /t 5 && net localgroup Administrators root /add. This payload will create a new user called root and add it in the administrators group with the password as Password123!. The full command I executed is python3 exp.py 10.10.105.255 'net user root Password123! /add && timeout /t 5 && net localgroup Administrators root /add' and obtained the result shown above. The target machine successfully executed the command. Can I RDP into the target machine now with the credentials root:Password123!? Time to found it.


To RDP into the target machine, I used the command xfreerdp /u:root /p:'Password123!' /v:10.10.105.255 and gained access to the target machine as the new user root as shown above. Now I have an RDP foothold on the target machine with administrator privileges as shown above. GG.

Flags


The flags are located at Desktop of the user Nekrotic, as shown above. I am able to successfully read the user.txt, but I do not have enough privileges to read the root.txt. Maybe I can edit the privileges?


I noticed the root.txt is not readable. To overcome this, I edited the privileges as shown above. Now this new user has the permissions to read the content of this file, as shown above.
